The presidential couple then has a scheduled meeting with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremonial ceremony at which Obama will take the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth president of the United States, but only the third to receive the award directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the Afghan War when he receives the award.
The president does not want to avoid this issue, because he realizes that he is taking over the prize as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
A few days ago, he stepped up his war effort by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which he will not forget to highlight any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to give for charitable purposes, but has not yet decided on a specific charity.
The President’s busy program will then be introduced to the banquet, where, in addition to the Norwegian King and Queen, there will also be the Prime Minister and 250 other invited guests.
From the very beginning, Obama was reluctant to pay the price.
For example, he said he felt that he did not deserve it.
