USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It’s only comical how schoolboy Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest, repeats his predecessor’s strategy in the Afghan question, which he himself considered to be the stupidest.
When he finally encapsulated his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had written it through a copy of Bush’s Iraq script three years ago.
Not only does he use the wording "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not hesitate even to use the name of Bush's January 2007 declaration as the name of his own declaration: "The New Way forward".
Three years ago, he criticised Bush’s idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to Iraq plagued by a civil war as “irresponsible and in its consequences catastrophic decisions.”
But the months that followed showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of the field commanders, was the only one that was so successful and so successful that today there is no talk of Iraq at all in the intelligence reports.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, but he objectively left his successor with a much more grateful starting situation than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
He was again asked to increase his military contingent by field commanders, especially Afghan Operation Commander General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the hesitant gunmen in the White House despite subordinate customs.
He asked 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn't get any better, so at least he smashed the general by 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to keep the promise of another 5,000 from Europe, even though he initially counted at least 10.
The most problematic part of Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to start pulling troops out of Afghanistan in 18 months and end the process in three years, and the entire Obama doctrine raises more questions than provides answers.
Many doubt that a half-increase will bear the same fruit as the process in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal war of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honor the agreement.
The situation in Afghanistan is marked by the opposite symptom - no one can be trusted and no agreements are being observed.
Under these conditions, the Afghan security forces are ill-prepared, accustomed to changing the master every day according to how it suits them.
Political institutions, even if they are formally established, will remain only a post-Mohammed village, after which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to thrive.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is unusually complex given the opaqueness of the conditions, which further complicate Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Nor does the construction of a “accessible state”, which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation, seem too real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is filled with its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only deteriorated and is now on the brink of an explosion.
To believe that the soldiers sent to the turret for the purpose of "short return home" will cause the miracle done here, only the soul can truly romantic, untouched reality.
From a political point of view, setting the date of the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will perceive it as an indirect confession of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit has shown that Europeans’ willingness to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is at a disadvantage.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their constituents how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of Hindukusha.
Another factor capable of radically interfering with the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the sanctions on Iran do not affect it, the United States will be faced with an overburdened question of not trying to solve the problem by military force.
It will need to be answered right at a time when, according to Obama, America is stepping up to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
Any such solution, however, will also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only placard for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left for the presidential election, and so there is still enough time for him to come up with another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
