About one percent of people get schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime, in psychiatric clinics it is the second most frequently treated disease after depression.
With acute schizophrenic psychosis, the affected can no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, they get into an exaggerated state that can lead to hallucinations, sizing, relationship illusions, or the illusion of persecution.
Particularly widespread is the hearing of voices - voices that command, comment or conduct dialogues.
Even optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The affected person is unable to distinguish important from unimportant, the brain cannot filter out disruptive signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream, psychosis opens up a flood of thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Clinics of General Psychiatry at the University Clinic in Heidelberg.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the event, everything has meaning directed at it.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, becomes, like in a dream, overwhelmed by events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
Comparing with reality is usually not possible with them, ghosts are a terrible reality, awakening is excluded.
Once in a lifetime experience hallucinations
Unlike in a dream, Fuchss says, “but the sensory and spatial structure of the reality that one perceives in psychosis remains fundamentally preserved.”
Stupid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place within the real framework.
Scientists are still facing a puzzle as to why our brains are making such messes.
“Extraordinary conditions can lead to a short-term loss of a relationship with reality,” says Fuchs.
Not everyone develops into a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Scientists believe that people with disabilities have minimal brain damage.
We believe that in the early stages of development, neuronal maturation of the brain will be damaged, for example by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
However, it remains a mystery as to how there will be a breakdown of the neural system, which has not been manifested in any way for many years.
The influences of the environment also play a role – stress or traumatic experiences can be the initiator of psychosis if there is a disposition for it.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmission system.
When our brains are boiling
It’s crazy that psychotronics suffer from their hallucinations, and to get rid of them, they swallow expensive drugs, others give money for drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten from Lübeck.
If we perceive delusions as pleasant or unpleasant, it is often just a question of attitude.
Casten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and delusions for ten years, last year interpreting his results in the book "Die unreale Welt in unserem Kopf".
While hallucinations are among the typical accompanying phenomena of psychosis, they are also surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline personality or depression, often diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s or brain trauma.
Surprisingly, it hallucinates the brain of a healthy person under certain conditions.
According to Kasten, hallucinations consist of the contents of thoughts that are normally suppressed.
They occur when the parts of the brain in which sensory perception is processed are too active or less suppressed; when our brain is boiling, or when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also withdrawal of stimuli, stress, worries with love or other exceptional states.
In more recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported that they experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
