Since she contacted Kasten's psychologist online, she knows exactly that she didn't go crazy.
Too much is also the art of desperation.
If someone is socially isolated or stimuli are taken away, they’re likely to have hallucinations, Kasten says.
I think the brain then doesn't have enough jobs and takes care of its own fun.
Sarah K., single, as a little girl, was afraid of other children, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man her father calls her from the time she thinks he is not her own father.
Because visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same areas of the brain that also process real senses and sounds, it is difficult for people like Sarah K. to distinguish between delusions and reality. "Each experience," says Kasten, "is also a reality.
Hallucinations are also images that allow the brain to form, which is why they act so real.”
Also, the night dreams evaluate Casten as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations in healthy people are not fundamentally different from hallucinations in acute psychosis.
In contrast to schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Casten therefore advises his patients to value hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
The boundary state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our overly conscious world, the imaginary experience is mostly pathologised, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the psychiatric and psychotherapeutic clinic at Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a difficult, painful disease, but it also brings positive, creativity - overcrowding is also the art of desperation.
Schmidt-Degenhard explored the so-called oneiroid form of experiences, a peculiar form of altered dream consciousness.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictitious dreams that the affected person considers to be real and cannot even distinguish them retrospectively from the waking state.
Oneiroid state of consciousness occurs in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example, patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor degeneration with full consciousness.
When a person is endangered by the loss of the world and himself, such as a persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces life-threatening real situations with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of border state between dream and hallucination.
Because in reality it is not possible to cope with a situation, worlds will change, but the real situation will be present in the imagination.
An intense form of support for the senses and the transfer of the senses into some unbearable situation, which allows us to pass our own capacity to form within a moment into the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even in later memories.
Also art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen describes his one-irode experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a saving action of the soul.
He was 49 years old when, after a heartbeat surgery with a subsequent heart transplant, his consciousness turned on a several-day journey, with his body lying stationary on the intensive care unit.
Claussen dived into the world he created, visited foreign times and places: He becomes an old man clinging to his bed, in a train sanatorium, a robot guarding his health.
It lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility that produces intoxicating substances from the blood.
On a motorcycle, he is kidnapped by a Greek man to his homeland, surfs on a hospital bed in the Alps and meets a Korean mafia.
It submerges itself completely into the imaginary story, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Clausen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a different state, it describes its experience.
In contrast to dreams, the memories of these mental journeys are still clear after years and in insignificant details.
Even brighter and more intense than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other real experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, oneiroid states, psychoses, hallucinations and drug intoxication show how fragile our inner images of external reality are even in a vigilant state.
Every change in the state of consciousness, concludes Kasten, “can lead to a deformation of what we call reality.”
A reality that can also be enriching.
