75% of working mothers have problems with maternity work.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among women of younger age who are planning to have a child.
This is the result of a study ‘Fertility and working careers of Spanish women’ conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Women’s Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75, and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labour market due to maternity.
The study emphasizes that at the beginning of partner cohabitation, there are many differences in views on the number of children depending on whether they work or not, and also according to the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with their partner earlier, give birth to their first child, and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, defer partnership cohabitation and maternity, and have fewer offspring.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have their first child, on average, 3.7 years since the beginning of cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving their stable employment and therefore had to postpone their partner cohabitation as well as their income.
The type of profession also has a strong impact on maternity, although a minor impact on the time of initiation of cohabitation with a partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, a researcher at CSIC.
Another factor influencing the age of women at the time of marriage is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the degree of education, the higher the age at which women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group 35-49, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 or 32.1.
“There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with basic education get married and give birth to their first child before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education prefer to have a stable job, before marriage and the birth of their first child.
